Advantages of Microservices

âœ” Scalability

Scale only the service that needs it (e.g., Payments on sale day)

âœ” Faster development

Multiple teams can work independently

âœ” Fault isolation

If Payment Service fails, Product Service still works

âœ” Easier CI/CD

Deploy small changes without full redeploy

Disadvantages (Always mention this)

âŒ Complexity

Many services = harder to manage

âŒ Network latency

API calls are slower than method calls

âŒ Data consistency

No easy joins across databases

âŒ DevOps overhead

Needs Docker, Kubernetes, monitoring, logging

âš ï¸ Interview tip: Say â€œMicroservices are not always better than monolithsâ€

Monolith vs Microservices (Quick Comparison)
Monolith	Microservices
Single codebase	Multiple services
Simple to start	Complex to manage
Hard to scale	Easy to scale
One deployment	Independent deployments
When should we use Microservices?

Use when:

Large application

Multiple teams

High scalability required

Frequent deployments

Avoid when:

Small app

Small team

Simple requirements

Common Interview Follow-up Questions

Be ready for these ğŸ‘‡

Why microservices instead of monolith?

How do services communicate?

How is data managed?

What challenges did you face?

How do you deploy microservices? (Docker/Kubernetes)

How do you handle failures? (Circuit breaker, retries)

30-second Interview Answer (Memorize This)

Microservices is an architectural style where an application is built as a set of small, independent services. Each service handles a specific business function, has its own database, and communicates with other services via APIs. This allows independent scaling, deployment, and better fault isolation, but increases operational complexity.-